    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses risks arising from incorrect application of the simulation tool by an end-user in a clinical or operational setting (e.g. mis-specification of boundary conditions by a non-expert analyst). In the Morrison COU2 context, the CFD model is executed exclusively by a qualified computational engineering team under a controlled SQA framework (see Software Quality Assurance factor). All simulation inputs are defined by a formal protocol document reviewed by the principal investigator prior to each run. The operating team holds documented competency records for ANSYS Fluent rotational machinery simulations. Because the model is not exposed to end-user variation outside this controlled execution environment, and because the SQA factor already captures procedural safeguards against analyst error, the incremental credibility contribution of a separate Use Error assessment is negligible at MRL 5. Scoping this factor out is consistent with ASME V&V 40 guidance that factors may be excluded when their risk contribution is adequately controlled by other assessed factors and the exclusion is documented with rationale."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cf/equiv-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters evaluates whether the input parameter space of the validation experiments adequately represents the input parameter space of the COU. In the Morrison COU2 assessment, the validation dataset (FDA generic pump benchmark, Stewart et al. 2012) was specifically designed to span the identical operating envelope as the COU: the same five flow-rate/rotational-speed combinations are present in both the experimental dataset and the COU specification. Because the validation and COU input spaces are co-designed and co-extensive by construction, there is no gap to characterise between them, and a separate Equivalency of Input Parameters assessment would be tautological. Furthermore, the Model Inputs credibility factor (assessed at Gradation 4) already documents the uncertainty distributions of all influential inputs and their propagation through Monte Carlo analysis, providing quantitative coverage of input-space representativeness. Scoping this factor out is therefore justified on grounds of redundancy and co-extensive input space design, consistent with ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3 guidance on factor applicability."
    }
  ],
